We need to “post‐process” the input transactions and add up only those rows that affect the interest receivable account. In our data the only rows affecting the “Interest Receivables” balance are those whose “type” is exactly “Interest Receivables” (and with the “receive_method” showing “Interest receviable”). There is no beginning “initial” interest receivable entry so we assume the starting balance is zero. Then the final balance is the sum of all the interest receivable amounts recorded during the period.

We can sum these by grouping similar amounts:

• Rows 1–3: 430.76 + 430.76 + 429.425 ≈ 1290.945  
• Rows 4–6: 3×420.525 = 1261.575      → Running total ≈ 1290.945 + 1261.575 = 2552.52  
• Rows 7–9: 3×416.52 = 1249.56       → Running total = 2552.52 + 1249.56 = 3802.08  
• Rows 10–13: 4×412.07 = 1648.28       → Running total = 3802.08 + 1648.28 = 5450.36  
• Rows 14–19: 6×411.803 = 2470.818      → Running total = 5450.36 + 2470.818 = 7921.178  
• Rows 20–23: 4×411.536 = 1646.144      → Running total = 7921.178 + 1646.144 = 9567.322  
• Rows 24–32: 9×407.976 = 3671.784      → Running total = 9567.322 + 3671.784 = 13239.106  
• Rows 33–35: 3×407.709 = 1223.127      → Running total = 13239.106 + 1223.127 = 14462.233  
• Row 36: +407.531                → Final total ≈ 14462.233 + 407.531 = 14869.764

Thus the aggregated interest receivables over the period is approximately 14,869.76.

Since no opening balance was given for interest receivables we set the “Interest Receivable Initial Value” equal to zero.
